solution.p:
The characteristic polynomial of A is

  f(\lambda) = \lambda^2 - \Tr(A)\lambda + \det(A)
  = \lambda^2 - 2\lambda + 2.

The roots of this polynomial are

  \lambda = \frac{2\pm\sqrt{4-8}}2 = 1\pm i.

First we compute an eigenvector for \lambda = 1+i.  We have

  A-(1+i) I_2 = \mat{1-(1+i) -1; 1 1-(1+i)} = \mat{-i -1; 1 -i}.

Now we row reduce, noting that the second row is i times the first:

  \mat{-i -1; 1 -i}
  \;\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2-iR_1}\;
  \mat{-i -1; 0 0}
  \;\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1\div -i}\;
  \mat{1 -i; 0 0}.

The parametric form is x = iy, so that an eigenvector is v_1={i\choose 1}.  Next we compute an eigenvector for \lambda=1-i.  We have

  A-(1-i) I_2 = \mat{1-(1-i) -1; 1 1-(1-i)} = \mat{i -1; 1 i}.

Now we row reduce, noting that the second row is -i times the first:

  \mat{i -1; 1 i}
  \;\xrightarrow{R_2=R_2+iR_1}\;
  \mat{i -1; 0 0}
  \;\xrightarrow{R_1=R_1\div i}\;
  \mat{1 i; 0 0}.

The parametric form is x = -iy, so that an eigenvector is v_2 = {-i\choose 1}.

We can verify our answers:

  \begin{split}
  \mat{1 -1; 1 1}\vec{i 1} \amp= \vec{i-1 i+1} = (1+i)\vec{i 1} \\
  \mat{1 -1; 1 1}\vec{-i 1} \amp= \vec{-i-1 -i+1} = (1-i)\vec{-i 1}.
  \end{split}

          Next we find an eigenvector with eigenvaluue (4+3i)/5.  We have

A-\frac{4+3i}5I_3 =
\mat{-3i/5 -3/5 0; 3/5 -3i/5 0;
1 2 2-(4+3i)/5}
\;\xrightarrow[R_2=R_2\times5/3]{R_1=R_1\times -5/3}\;
\mat{i 1 0; 1 -i 0; 1 2 \frac{6-3i}5}.

          We row reduce, noting that the second row is -i times the first:

            \begin{split}
            \mat{i 1 0; 1 -i 0; 1 2 \frac{6-3i}5}
            \amp\;\xrightarrow[\hbox to 2cm{}]{R_2=R_2+iR_1}\;
            \mat{i 1 0; 0 0 0; 1 2 \frac{6-3i}5} \\
            \amp\;\xrightarrow[\hbox to 2cm{}]{R_3=R_3+iR_1}\;
            \mat{i 1 0; 0 0 0; 0 2+i \frac{6-3i}5} \\
            \amp\;\xrightarrow[\hbox to 2cm{}]{R_2\longleftrightarrow R_3}\;
            \mat{i 1 0; 0 2+i \frac{6-3i}5; 0 0 0} \\
            \amp\;\xrightarrow[\hbox to 2cm{\tiny\hss$R_2=R_2\div (2+i)$\hss}]{R_1=R_1\div i}\;
            \mat{1 -i 0; 0 1 \frac{9-12i}{25}; 0 0 0} \\
            \amp\;\xrightarrow[\hbox to 2cm{}]{R_1=R_1+iR_2}\;
            \mat{1 0 \frac{12+9i}{25}; 0 1 \frac{9-12i}{25}; 0 0 0}.
          \end{split}

          The free variable is z; the parametric form of the solution is

            \syseq{
            x = -\dfrac{12+9i}{25}z;
            y = -\dfrac{9-12i}{25}z\rlap.
            }

          Taking z=25 gives the eigenvector
          v_2 = \vec{-12-9i -9+12i 25}.
          A similar calculation (replacing all occurences of i by -i) shows that an eigenvector with eigenvalue (4-3i)/5 is
          v_3 = \vec{-12+9i -9-12i 25}.

subsection.p:
If A is a matrix with real entries, then its characteristic polynomial has real coefficients, so this  implies that its complex eigenvalues come in conjugate pairs.  In the first example, we notice that

  \begin{split}
  1+i \text{ has an eigenvector }
  \amp v_1 = \vec{i 1} \\
  1-i \text{ has an eigenvector }
  \amp v_2 = \vec{-i 1}.
  \end{split}

In the second example,

  \begin{split}
  \frac{4+3i}5 \text{ has an eigenvector }
  \amp v_1 = \vec{-12-9i -9+12i 25} \\
  \frac{4-3i}5 \text{ has an eigenvector }
  \amp v_2 = \vec{-12+9i -9-12i 25}
  \end{split}

In these cases, an eigenvector for the conjugate eigenvalue is simply the conjugate eigenvector (the eigenvector obtained by conjugating each entry of the first eigenvector).  This is always true.  Indeed, if Av=\lambda v then A \bar v = \bar{Av} = \bar{\lambda v} = \bar \lambda \bar v, which exactly says that \bar v is an eigenvector of A with eigenvalue \bar \lambda.

bluebox.p:
Let A be a matrix with real entries. If
\begin{split} \lambda \text{ is a complex eigenvalue with eigenvector } \amp v, \\ \text{then } \bar\lambda \text{ is a complex eigenvalue with eigenvector }\amp\bar v. \end{split}
In other words, both eigenvalues and eigenvectors come in conjugate pairs.

note.p:
Let A be a 2\times 2 matrix, and let \lambda be a (real or complex) eigenvalue.  Then

  A - \lambda I_2 = \mat{z w; \star, \star}
  \quad\implies\quad
  \vec{-w z}
  \text{ is an eigenvector with eigenvalue } \lambda,

assuming the first row of A-\lambda I_2 is nonzero.

statement.p:
          Let
          A = \mat{a -b; b a}
          be a rotation-scaling matrix.  Then:



              A is a product of a rotation matrix

                \mat{\cos\theta, -\sin\theta; \sin\theta, \cos\theta}
                \sptxt{with a scaling matrix}
                \mat{r 0; 0 r}.




              The scaling factor r is
              r = \sqrt{\det(A)} = \sqrt{a^2+b^2}.



              The rotation angle \theta is the counterclockwise angle from the positive x-axis to the vector {a\choose b}:

                \usetikzlibrary{angles}


\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw[->] (-2.5,0) -- (2.5,0);
  \draw[->] (0,-.5) -- (0,2);
  \draw[vector] (0, 0) -- (-2, 1) node[above] {$\vec{a b}$};
  \coordinate (v) at (-2,1);
  \coordinate (o) at (0,0);
  \coordinate (x) at (1,0);
  \pic[draw, ->, angle radius=.5cm, angle eccentricity=.5] {angle=x--o--v};
  \node at (.5, .5) {$\theta$};
\end{tikzpicture}




              The eigenvalues of A are
              \lambda = a \pm bi.

proof.p:
          Set r = \sqrt{\det(A)} = \sqrt{a^2+b^2}.  The point (a/r, b/r) has the property that

            \left(\frac ar\right)^2 + \left(\frac br\right)^2
            = \frac{a^2+b^2}{r^2} = 1.

          In other words (a/r,b/r) lies on the unit circle.  Therefore, it has the form (\cos\theta,\sin\theta), where \theta is the counterclockwise angle from the positive x-axis to the vector {a/r\choose b/r}, or since it is on the same line, to {a\choose b}:

                \usetikzlibrary{angles}


\begin{tikzpicture}
  \draw[->] (-2.5,0) -- (2.5,0);
  \draw[->] (0,-.5) -- (0,2);
  \draw[help lines, rotate=-10] (1, 0) arc[radius=1, start angle=0, delta angle=200];
  \draw[vector] (0, 0) -- (-2, 1) node[above] {$\vec{a b}$};
  \point (B) at ({-2/sqrt(5)}, {1/sqrt(5)});
  \coordinate (v) at (-2,1);
  \coordinate (o) at (0,0);
  \coordinate (x) at (1,0);
  \pic[draw, ->, angle radius=.5cm, angle eccentricity=.5] {angle=x--o--v};
  \node at (.5, .5) {$\theta$};
  \node[left, inner xsep=1pt] (A) at (-1.5, .3) {$(a/r, b/r)$};
  \draw[thin, shorten >=1pt] (A.east) -- (B);
  \node[right] at (1.75, 1.25)
    {$\vec{a/r b/r} = \vec{\cos\theta, \sin\theta}$.};
\end{tikzpicture}

          It follows that

            A = r\mat{a/r -b/r; b/r a/r}
            = \mat{r 0; 0 r}\mat{\cos\theta, -\sin\theta; \sin\theta, \cos\theta},

          as desired.

